Data analysis

Table

fse

We fitted a linear mixed model (estimated using REML and nloptwrap optimizer) to predict fse with age, group and time_point (formula: fse ~ 1 + age + group + time_point + group * time_point). The model included login_id as random effect (formula: ~1 | login_id). The models total explanatory power is substantial (conditional R2 = 0.68) and the part related to the fixed effects alone (marginal R2) is of 0.16. The models intercept, corresponding to age = 0, group = control and time_point = 1st , is at 14.76 (S.E. = 2.72, p < .001, 95% CI [9.43, 20.09]). Within this model:

  • The effect of age is statistically non-significant and positive (beta = 0.07, S.E. = 0.04, p = 0.108, 95% CI [-0.02, 0.16]; Std. beta = 0.27, 95% CI [-0.06, 0.61])
  • The effect of group [treatment] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.95, S.E. = 1.34, p = 0.478, 95% CI [-3.57, 1.67]; Std. beta = -0.26, 95% CI [-0.98, 0.46])
  • The effect of time point [2nd] is statistically non-significant and negative (beta = -0.66, S.E. = 0.88, p = 0.450, 95% CI [-2.38, 1.05]; Std. beta = -0.18, 95% CI [-0.65, 0.29])
  • The interaction effect of time point [2nd] on group [treatment] is statistically significant and positive (beta = 4.23, S.E. = 1.28, p < .001, 95% CI [1.72, 6.75]; Std. beta = 1.17, 95% CI [0.47, 1.86])

Standardized parameters were obtained by fitting the model on a standardized version of the dataset. 95% Confidence Intervals (CIs) and p-values were computed using a Wald normal distribution approximation.
